<note xml:id="ch17n194"><p id="ch17n194pa1">We might derive an additional supply of 301,750 inhabitants from the dioceses of Châlons (<hi rend="italic">Cabillonum</hi>) and of Macon (<hi rend="italic">Matisco</hi>); since they contain, the one 200, and the other 260, parishes. This accession of territory might be justified by very specious reasons. 1. Châlons and Macon were undoubtedly within the original jurisdiction of the Aedui (see d'Anville, Notice, p. 187, 443). 2. In the <hi rend="italic">Notitia</hi> of Gaul, they are enumerated not as <hi rend="italic">Civitates,</hi> but merely as <hi rend="italic">Castra.</hi> 3. They do not appear to have been episcopal seats before the fifth and sixth centuries. Yet there is a passage in Eumenius (Panegyr. Vet. viii. 7) which very forcibly deters me from extending the territory of the Aedui, in the reign of Constantine, along the beautiful banks of the navigable Sâone.</p></note>

