<note xml:id="ch19n32"><p id="ch19n32pa1">Libanius and Gregory Nazianzen have exhausted the arts as well as the powers of their eloquence, to represent Julian as the first of heroes, or the worst of tyrants. Gregory was his fellow-student at Athens; and the symptoms, which he so tragically describes, of the future wickedness of the apostate amount only to some bodily imperfections and to some peculiarities in his speech and manner. He protests, however, that he <hi rend="italic">then</hi> foresaw and foretold the calamities of the church and state (Greg. Nazianzen, Orat. iv. p. 121, 122). [See Libanius, <hi rend="italic">Epitaphios,</hi> 526 <hi rend="italic">sqq.,</hi> ed. Reiske.]</p></note>

